First clarify terminology: in a rooted binary tree the root is an ancestor of every node, so the "highest common ancestor" (the common ancestor closest to the root) of any two nodes that both exist in the tree is just the root. I assume you actually meant the usual programming problem, the lowest common ancestor (LCA) — the common ancestor nearest the two nodes. Below I give a short Python implementation for both interpretations:

- Highest common ancestor (literal): returns root if both nodes exist, otherwise None.
- Lowest common ancestor (LCA): standard recursive solution that returns the deepest common ancestor.

Code (Python):

class TreeNode:
    def __init__(self, val=0, left=None, right=None):
        self.val = val
        self.left = left
        self.right = right

def contains(root, target):
    if root is None:
        return False
    if root is target:
        return True
    return contains(root.left, target) or contains(root.right, target)

def highest_common_ancestor(root, p, q):
    # literal "highest" = ancestor closest to root -> the root itself (if both nodes present)
    if root is None:
        return None
    if not contains(root, p) or not contains(root, q):
        return None
    return root

def lowest_common_ancestor(root, p, q):
    # returns None if neither node found; if one node is in the tree it returns that node
    if root is None:
        return None
    if root is p or root is q:
        return root
    left = lowest_common_ancestor(root.left, p, q)
    right = lowest_common_ancestor(root.right, p, q)
    if left and right:
        return root
    return left if left else right

